            <figcaption>Geometry Dash features vibrant visuals and challenging obstacle courses synchronized with music</figcaption>
          </figure>

          <p>The game operates on a simple principle: "Die and Retry." Each level failure sends you back to the beginning, but the game is designed so that you learn from each attempt. This addictive gameplay loop has made Geometry Dash one of the most popular <a href="/c/platformer-games/">platformer games</a> on mobile platforms and web browsers. The game has received numerous updates, with the highly anticipated <a href="https://geometry-dash.fandom.com/wiki/Update_2.2" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Update 2.2</a> bringing exciting new features and gameplay mechanics.</p>

          <h2 id="how-to-play">How to Play Geometry Dash</h2>
          <p>Playing Geometry Dash is simple to learn but challenging to master. Your character moves automatically from left to right across the screen. Your only control is making your character jump. The timing of your jumps is critical—you must jump at exactly the right moment to avoid obstacles and reach the end of each level.</p>

          <h3>Basic Controls</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>PC:</strong> Press spacebar, click left mouse button, or press up arrow to jump</li>
            <li><strong>Mobile:</strong> Tap anywhere on the screen to jump</li>
            <li><strong>Keyboard:</strong> Use arrow keys or WASD for alternative controls</li>
          </ul>

          <p>The key to success is listening to the music and watching the patterns. Most obstacles appear in sync with the beat, so experienced players use the soundtrack as a guide for when to jump. This synchronization between <a href="/c/music-games/">music and gameplay</a> is what makes Geometry Dash unique among <a href="/c/geometry-games/">geometry platformers</a>.</p>

          <h2 id="gameplay-mechanics">Gameplay Mechanics</h2>
          <p>Geometry Dash features several core mechanics that define the gameplay experience:</p>

          <h3>Gravity and Physics</h3>
          <p>Your character is affected by gravity, falling when not jumping. Different sections of levels feature gravity portals that reverse the direction of gravity, forcing you to adapt your jumping patterns. Understanding gravity mechanics is essential for progression.</p>

          <h3>Speed Changes</h3>
          <p>Throughout levels, you'll encounter speed portals that increase or decrease your movement speed. These changes require you to adjust your timing accordingly. Faster sections demand quicker reflexes, while slower sections allow for more deliberate jumps.</p>

          <h3>Obstacle Types</h3>
          <p>Geometry Dash features various obstacle types including spikes, moving platforms, rotating obstacles, and more. Each obstacle type requires different strategies to overcome. Learning to recognize and respond to each obstacle type is crucial for beating difficult levels.</p>

          <h2 id="game-modes">Game Modes and Character Forms</h2>
          <p>One of Geometry Dash's defining features is the variety of game modes. Your character transforms into different forms, each with unique physics and controls:</p>

          <h3>The Cube Form</h3>
          <p>The cube is your default form. It jumps over obstacles with standard gravity physics. This is the most intuitive form and is used in most levels. Master the cube form first before attempting other character types.</p>

          <h3>The Ship Form</h3>
          <p>In ship mode, your character flies up and down instead of jumping. Tapping makes you go up, and releasing makes you go down. This form requires smooth, controlled movements and is often considered more difficult than the cube.</p>

          <h3>The Ball Form</h3>
          <p>The ball bounces and switches gravity with every tap. It demands very precise timing and is challenging for most players. The ball form teaches you about gravity mechanics and momentum.</p>

          <h3>The UFO Form</h3>
          <p>The UFO hovers and requires you to control its vertical position. This form is less common but appears in specific level sections. It requires a different approach than other forms.</p>

          <h3>The Wave Form</h3>
          <p>The wave moves up and down in a wave-like pattern. Tapping controls its vertical position. This form is particularly challenging and requires excellent timing.</p>

          <h3>The Robot Form</h3>
          <p>The robot can jump multiple times, making it more forgiving than other forms. It's often used in easier sections or as a reward for skilled players.</p>

          <h3>The Spider Form</h3>
          <p>The spider can climb on surfaces and walls. This form opens up new level design possibilities and requires players to think differently about navigation.</p>

          <h2 id="difficulty-levels">Difficulty Levels</h2>
          <p>Geometry Dash features a wide range of difficulty levels, from beginner-friendly to impossibly hard:</p>

          <h3>Easy Levels (1-2 stars)</h3>
          <p>Perfect for learning the basics. These levels teach fundamental mechanics with simple obstacles and straightforward patterns. Beginners should start here.</p>

          <h3>Medium Levels (3-4 stars)</h3>
          <p>Intermediate challenges that introduce multiple game modes and more complex patterns. These levels require solid fundamentals and practice.</p>

          <h3>Hard Levels (5-6 stars)</h3>
          <p>Challenging levels that demand precision and pattern memorization. These levels are where most players struggle and need significant practice.</p>

          <h3>Insane Levels (7-8 stars)</h3>
          <p>Extremely difficult levels requiring expert-level skills. Only experienced players should attempt these levels.</p>

          <h3>Extreme Levels (9-10 stars)</h3>
          <p>The hardest levels in the game. These are designed for the most skilled players and require hundreds of attempts to complete.</p>

          <h2 id="tips-and-tricks">Tips and Tricks for Success</h2>
          <p>Here are expert tips to help you improve your Geometry Dash skills:</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Listen to the music:</strong> The soundtrack is your guide. Obstacles sync with the beat, so use the music to anticipate jumps</li>
            <li><strong>Use practice mode:</strong> Place checkpoints to practice difficult sections without restarting from the beginning</li>
            <li><strong>Study patterns:</strong> Watch how obstacles move and appear. Understanding patterns is key to success</li>
            <li><strong>Don't rush:</strong> Focus on consistency over speed. Accurate jumps matter more than fast reactions</li>
            <li><strong>Take breaks:</strong> Playing when frustrated leads to mistakes. Step away and return with fresh eyes</li>
            <li><strong>Watch tutorials:</strong> Watching experienced players can teach you new techniques and strategies</li>
            <li><strong>Practice specific sections:</strong> Use practice mode to master difficult parts before attempting full levels</li>
            <li><strong>Learn from failures:</strong> Each failed attempt teaches you something. Analyze what went wrong</li>
            <li><strong>Stay calm:</strong> Panic leads to mistakes. Maintain focus and composure during difficult sections</li>
            <li><strong>Customize your character:</strong> Unlock and use icons that help you see your character better</li>
          </ul>

